Though completely swamped, the boat was nearly unharmed.  Ere the squall came close to, the other boats had cut loose from their fish and returned to the ship in good time. 

Soon we were running through a suffusing wide veil of mist; neither ship nor boat to be seen. 

Meantime, Ahab, out of hearing of his officers, having sided the furthest to windward, was still ranging ahead of the other boats; a circumstance bespeaking how potent a crew was pulling him.  He loaded it, and rammed home the loading with his thumb-end; but hardly had he ignited his match across the rough sandpaper of his hand, when Tashtego, his harpooneer, whose eyes had been setting to windward like two fixed stars, suddenly dropped like light from his erect attitude to his seat, crying out in a quick phrensy of hurry, "Down, down all, and give way!--there they are!"  Those tiger yellow creatures of his seemed all steel and whalebone; like five trip-hammers they rose and fell with regular strokes of strength, which periodically started the boat along the water like a horizontal burst boiler out of a Mississippi steamer.  The White Whale's at the bottom of it.  That's it--that's it!  Stubb!  long and strong.  Affrighted, we all sprang into the sea as the ship at last loomed into view, bearing right down upon us within a distance of not much more than its length.  Seen in advance of all the other indications, the puffs of vapour they spouted, seemed their forerunning couriers and detached flying outriders.  On his broad back, flaxen-haired Flask seemed a snow-flake.  Beneath this atmospheric waving and curling, and partially beneath a thin layer of water, also, the whales were swimming. 

It was a sight full of quick wonder and awe!  Didn't I hear 'em in the hold?  Spring!"  whispered Starbuck. 

